For the call() function and the type-erasure, I want to explain clearly:

The trick: `call: unsafe fn(*mut u8)` is a plain function pointer (not a trait object). But because `Deferred::new` is generic over `F`, the concrete `call::<F>` function is monomorphized per F. When we write `call: call::<F>`, we capture the *type* F into the choice of function pointer. So the function pointer "knows" F's type at compile time, while the `data` buffer holds F's runtime value. This is hand-rolled type erasure.

This is different from `dyn FnOnce()` which uses a vtable (fat pointer). Here we use a thin function pointer + a fixed data slot, which lets us control the data storage (inline vs box).

Let me also explain why `MaybeUninit`: the data buffer may hold F or Box<F>, and we don't want to auto-drop or zero-init it. `MaybeUninit<Data>` is the right type for "raw bytes that might or might not be initialized".

Now the Drop behavior: `Deferred` does NOT implement `Drop` itself. Instead, `Deferred::call(self)` consumes it by reading out the closure and calling it. But who calls `call`? The `Bag::drop` iterates and calls `.call()` on each. And `Deferred::NO_OP`'s `call` is `no_op_call` which does nothing — so even uninitialized/placeholder slots are safe (they point to no_op_call). Wait, but `Bag::Default` fills ALL slots with `Deferred::NO_OP`, and `try_push` overwrites slots up to `len`. So slots beyond `len` are NO_OP and would be safe even if called — but `Drop` only calls `[..self.len]`. The `mem::replace(deferred, no_op)` in Drop replaces each called one with NO_OP so that if Bag is partially dropped / re-dropped it's idempotent (defensive). Actually the reason for replace is: `call(self)` takes ownership, but we have `&mut self.deferreds[i]`, so we `mem::replace` to take it out, then call it. The replacement with NO_OP ensures the slot doesn't hold a stale valid Deferred that could double-execute. Good.

Let me also note: `Deferred::call` takes `mut self` (ownership) and does NOT manually drop `self.data` — because after `ptr::read` moves F out, the data buffer is "moved out" and the MaybeUninit has no Drop. So no double-free. The `ptr::read` is a bitwise copy out, leaving the source logically uninitialized. Since MaybeUninit has no Drop, dropping the `Deferred` after call won't touch the buffer. Good.

